Scrolling, Ads, and Algorithms

So I opened my phone and guess what I saw?

When I open a social media app and start scrolling, the first thing I usually see is an ad not from a friend, but from a brand or channnel. And based on the data I logged, the algorithm clearly has favourites.

Most first ads I encountered were for entertainment and fashion. These categories consistently appeared at the top of the feed, suggesting theyre being prioritised either because of what I engage with, or because they perform well with others in my demographic. So we now know what kinds of ads pop up first, but lets see if they are actually relevant to me?

Is the algorithm stalking me or just guessing?

Ad relevance

This plot shows which platforms had ads that felt the most relevant to my interests. Unsurprisingly, Instagram dominates, with most of its ads being tagged as relevant by me. Thats either impressive targeting or slightly scary. TikTok, on the other hand, had more somewhat relevant ads, which might reflect a more generalised feed or broader ad pool. The algorithm knows what I like, especially on Instagram. But relevance isnt evenly distributed, and not every platform gets me.

When are the ads hitting hardest?

Which time of the day had ads

Heres when I was hit with the most ads. Throughout the day, things were pretty balanced until around 1 PM, when there was a noticeable spike.

Maybe thats lunchtime scrolling, maybe thats just me being bored. Either way, platforms seem to push ads when Im most likely to scroll.

How long do I stay trapped in the scroll?!

Scroll Time Ranges

Some scrolls last two minutes. Others not so much.

This plot shows how long I stayed on each platform durring each scroll session recorded. Instagram? Quick check-ins under 10 minutes. TikTok? Thats where time disappears. Most of my longer sessions were there, between 2030 minutes.

Its interesting how different platforms pull me in for different lengths of time. Not every app is equally addictive but they all know how to keep me looking just long enough to drop another ad.

So what did I learn?

This scroll diary taught me that ads arent random. Platforms carefully decide what I see, when I see it, and how long I stay. Some are better at relevance, some at attention-grabbing, and some just keep me there longer than I mean to be.
